{{About|the British physicist|his son, the British computer scientist|Peter Buneman}} {{Infobox scientist | name = | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = <!--(as myimage.jpg, no 'File:')--> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_date = {{Birth date|1913|9|28|df=y}} | birth_place = | death_date = {{Death date and age|1993|1|24|1913|9|28|df=y}} | death_place = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline,title}} --> | other_names = | residence = | citizenship = | nationality = | fields = | workplaces = [[Stanford University]]<ref name="tribute"/> | alma_mater = [[University of Manchester]]<ref name="mathgene"/> | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | doctoral_advisor = [[Douglas Hartree]]<ref name="mathgene">{{MathGenealogy|id=140769}}</ref> | academic_advisors = | doctoral_students = [[John Holdren]]<ref name="holdrenphd">{{cite thesis |degree=PhD |first=John Paul|last=Holdren |title=Collisionless Stability of an Inhomogeneous, Confied, Planar Plasma |publisher=Stanford University |date=1970 |url=http://search.proquest.com/docview/302557782|authorlink=John Holdren}}</ref>
| notable_students = | known_for = | author_abbrev_bot = | author_abbrev_zoo = | influences = | influenced = | awards = | signature = <!--(filename only)--> | signature_alt = | website = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} --> | footnotes = | spouse = | children = [[Peter Buneman]] }} '''Oscar Buneman''' (28 September 1913 – 24 January 1993) made advances in [[science]], [[engineering]], and [[mathematics]]. Buneman was a pioneer of computational [[plasma physics]] and [[Plasma (physics)|plasma]] simulation.<ref name="tribute">{{Cite journal | last1 = Buneman | first1 = R. | last2 = Barker | first2 = R. J. | last3 = Peratt | first3 = A. L. | last4 = Brecht | first4 = S. H. | last5 = Langdon | first5 = A. B. | last6 = Lewis | first6 = H. R. | doi = 10.1109/27.281546 | title = A tribute to Oscar Buneman - pioneer of plasma simulation | journal = IEEE Transactions on Plasma Science | volume = 22 | pages = 22 | year = 1994 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref><ref name="scopus">{{Scopus|id=6603717293}}</ref>
==Career== In 1940 upon completion of his PhD with [[Douglas Hartree]],<ref name="mathgene"/> Buneman joined Hartree's magnetron research group assisting the development of radar during World War II. They discovered the Buneman–Hartree criterion for the voltage threshold of a magnetron operation. After the war, Buneman developed theories and simulations of collision-less dissipation of currents<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Buneman | first1 = O. | title = Dissipation of Currents in Ionized Media | doi = 10.1103/PhysRev.115.503 | journal = Physical Review | volume = 115 | issue = 3 | pages = 503 | year = 1959 | pmid = | pmc = }}</ref> called the Buneman instability. This is an example of [[:wikt:anomaly|anomalous]] [[resistivity]] or absorption. It is ''anomalous'' because the phenomenon does not depend on collisions. Buneman advanced [[elliptic equation]] solver methods and their associated applications (as well as for the [[fast Fourier transform]]s).
==Personal life== On January 24, 1993, Oscar Buneman at the age of 79 died near [[Stanford University]]. The [[computer scientist]] [[Peter Buneman]] is his son.
==Publications== * Buneman, O., "''Time reversible difference procedures''". Journal of Computers Physics. 1, 517 (1967). * Buneman, O., "''A compact non-iterative poisson-solver''". SUIPR report 294, Stanford University (1969). * Buneman, O., "''Fast numerical procedures for computer experiments on relativistic plasmas, in "Relativistic Plasmas (The Coral Gables Conference)''", Benjamin, NY, 1968. *{{Cite journal | last1 = Buneman | first1 = O. | title = Subgrid resolution of flow and force fields | doi = 10.1016/0021-9991(73)90006-5 | journal = Journal of Computational Physics | volume = 11 | issue = 2 | pages = 250–268 | year = 1973 | pmid = | pmc = }} * Buneman, O., and ''et al.'', "''Principles and capabilities of 3d EM particle simulations''". Journal of Computational Physics. 38, 1 (1980).
